# 🏨 Hotel Management System

A console-based Hotel Management System built in Java that allows users to manage hotel room bookings, customer records, and a first-come-first-served queue — all through an interactive menu interface.

---

## 📋 Features

| Option | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| **V** | View all rooms and their occupancy status |
| **A** | Add a customer to an available room |
| **E** | Display all currently empty rooms |
| **D** | Delete (vacate) a customer from a room |
| **F** | Find a room by customer name |
| **S** | Save current room data to a text file |
| **L** | Load room data back from the saved file |
| **O** | View all occupied rooms sorted alphabetically by name |
| **3** | Display and dequeue the first 3 customers in the waiting queue |
| **Q** | Quit the program |

---

## 🏗️ Project Structure

```
├── Main.java       # Entry point — initialises and launches the menu
├── Menu.java       # Core application logic and all menu operations
├── Room.java       # Room model with getter/setter for customer name
└── Queue.java      # Fixed-size queue (size 7) for customer registration order
```

### Class Overview

- **`Main`** — Bootstraps the application by creating a `Menu` object and calling `initialize()` then `menu()`.
- **`Menu`** — Contains all business logic: room management, file I/O (read/write `data.txt`), bubble sort for alphabetical ordering, and input validation with exception handling.
- **`Room`** — Simple POJO representing a hotel room. Rooms default to `"e"` (empty) on creation.
- **`Queue`** — Circular-style fixed-size queue that tracks customer check-in order. Automatically removes the front entry when the queue overflows (size 7). The `displayQueue()` method dequeues and prints the first 3 customers.

---

## 🚀 Getting Started

### Prerequisites

- Java JDK 8 or higher

### Compile

```bash
javac Main.java Menu.java Room.java Queue.java
```

### Run

```bash
java Main
```

---

## 💾 Data Persistence

Selecting **S** writes the current state of all 10 rooms to `data.txt` in the working directory. Empty rooms are stored as `Empty Room <number>` and customer names are stored as plain text, one per line.

Selecting **L** reads `data.txt` back and restores the room state into the program.

---

## ⚙️ Implementation Notes

- The hotel supports **10 rooms** (indexed 1–10).
- Input is case-insensitive for all menu selections and customer name searches.
- Robust exception handling covers `InputMismatchException`, `IndexOutOfBoundsException`, and `NullPointerException` across all user-input flows.
- Alphabetical ordering uses a **flag-based bubble sort** on a copy of the names array, preserving the original room assignments.
- The customer queue uses a fixed array of size **7**. When the queue is full, the front customer is automatically removed (FIFO eviction) to make room for the new entry.

